We have learned many useful tactical methods so far. The topic of today's lesson is "Edge Effect".
Renju is played on board with size 15 x15,
too small for black or white? :)
and that sets us a whole new area of tactics - to include the edge into our defense.
too small for attack, too large for defence
For the introduction of today's topic,
let me tell you about my discussion with farmer.
Farmer is a fan of corner renju.
He likes to challenge people in friendly games like this
Then one day he asked me,
where is the best white defense.
The j6 can defend against ANY black first move in the 5x5 corner square
Here, black will attempt to balance
and come out of the corner
to make the farmost move from cornert
and at the same time does not let black out form corner
white can use the 2-j6 anytime as long as the first move is inside 5x5 corner area
that regardless of the position of the first black stone
does anyone want to try blacks here?
who wants to try say ME

hoho ,let me try to use it
ok just for simplicity lets defend
more whites outside in every move
don't use any three which does not obey the three rules
it tried to follow the idea of manipulating with edge
as you saw, black could not come out from corner
and white would win the game later soon
so, the very first stone becomes a waste usually.
So, this game shows the importance of the edge.
That磗 why we start i H8
The j6 stone shows clearly the defense idea -
to cooperate with edge, to make lines short
so black cannot build threes on those lines.
but what can we do when the 1st is j6
Here, black can get a very good game
but if one step closer to corner
so we say, j6 is the key point of renju defense
so, maybe 13x13 is also a good board for renju? :)
Its almost d2 with small shift
Before we often played on Go-boards 19x19
so black can do fine here
This stone here actually cooperates with edge on 5 directions!!
Would 19x19 change the game very much??
the bigger the board,the better the black's chance
so, j6 is a powerful defense stone
This is so called "invisible" defender in every game
and people do not even know it.
Sometimes we wonder, why black seems so weak in attack
you just look who got the j6
the corner attack may be powerful
I will play 1 or 2 to j6
You also have to get J10, F6 and F10
This is not sure rule in every game, but the principle here is very strong,
And even top players do not know the j6 is the cause.
see, this stone only cooperates with edge on 3 directions.
Now many students will lose because they磍l get J6 and forget the real game !!!
so, it makes the j6 stone to be as effective as k5 in the sense of defense,
but its better than k6 in the sense of attack
From this "theory", lets move on to "practice"
the old renju game had 19x19 board
because in 19x19 the edge cannot help whites to defend.
Lets simulate this to be 19x19 board
lets say, the lower part applies for 19x19 size
the only defence white 16 for normal size of board
but in 15x15 the 32nd move is white win

As you know, the long theories sometimes last 40-50 moves,
Advanced players skilfully use the edge as a part of the defense plan.
The edge is nowadays one of the key questions in WC level.
Who can manipulate with edge best,
These two 5th moves look the same
but actually there are tens of variants
Do you remember, in the 2nd game with Nakamura, I offered 5-i7, 5-i6??
Nakamura thought long long time before accepting the 5th move
He had to replay hundreds of variants in his mind
with one line shifted at edge
He could not come to the conclusion,
but harder for black to win :)
So you wanted him to lose time??
would black benefit from this edge difference or white.
because I think it's closer to edge ...
the closeness of the opening stone to edge does not mean its weaker
the question is " where is the direction of the development"
sometimes the variant develops to the opposite direction fromt he 5th move
it depends about main attack corse
I wanted to change one move in the variant
The white gets very dangerous attack
but in my case, white would not have enough space
so I won the game fast,
because my opponent was confused by the tactics of 5th and 21st move.
looks like there are hundreds of wins
you realize it is soo hard to win
thanks to the strong defense stones of whites,
but at least you see, the j6 stone makes black attack so complicated despite the many lines of blacks
There are so many theories in renju which have the edge effect.

So, what we learned today is:
the edge is a very very important part of renju game
and the edge influences our attacks and defenses a lot.
The way the edge influences the games, I call it the "edge effect".
That is why I named today's lesson that way.
